      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study (coarse 2.1 M, medium 8.4 M, fine 33.6 M cells) performed at all 5 operating conditions. Grid convergence index (GCI) computed per Celik et al. (2008): GCI_fine < 1.8% for NIH at all conditions. Asymptotic range confirmed (GCI_medium/GCI_fine ≈ r^p). Fine mesh selected for all production runs. Temporal discretization error verified separately with CFL < 0.5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions documented with NIST-traceable calibration certificates for flow meters (±0.5%), torque transducers (±0.3%), and temperature sensors (±0.1 °C). Blood analog fluid (glycerin-water with PRBC) characterized rheologically at test temperature. All 5 operating points replicated in triplicate; coefficient of variation < 4% across replicates. Boundary conditions for CFD derived directly from calibrated experimental measurements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Quantitative validation metrics computed per ASME V&V 20: validation uncertainty U_val = 10.1%; model form error E = 6.2% (within U_val). Area validation metric (AVM) computed across all 5 conditions: AVM = 0.87 (scale 0–1, threshold 0.75 for MRL 5). Prediction intervals from Monte Carlo UQ envelope 94% of experimental observations. Formal hypothesis test (Wilcoxon signed-rank) confirms no systematic bias (p = 0.31)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Primary QoI is normalized index of hemolysis (NIH, mg/dL) — the direct clinical safety metric for VAD hemolysis assessment per ASTM F1841. Secondary QoIs (shear stress distribution, exposure time histogram) are mechanistically linked to NIH through the power-law damage model. Clinical relevance confirmed by consulting hematologist: NIH < 0.01 mg/dL corresponds to clinically acceptable chronic hemolysis for VAD use. QoI mapping documented in QoI specification document QS-COU2-2025."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/validation-relevance-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments performed on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry used in the COU. Operating conditions span the full VAD clinical envelope (flow 2–8 L/min, speed 2000–3500 RPM). Blood analog rheology matches in-vivo viscosity at physiological hematocrit (40%). Geometric fidelity confirmed by CMM measurement of impeller and volute against CAD nominal (max deviation 0.08 mm). Validation relevance score per Morrison Table 4: 9/10."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/solver-error-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence monitored via normalized residuals (< 1e-6 for all equations) and global mass/momentum imbalance (< 0.01%). Round-off error assessed by comparing double vs. extended-precision runs: difference < 0.1% in NIH. Floating-point reproducibility confirmed across HPC platforms (Intel and AMD nodes). Solver error budget contributes < 0.5% to total uncertainty budget documented in UQ report UQ-COU2-2025."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/use-error-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Simulation workflow executed under documented standard operating procedure SOP-CFD-VAD-003 (revision 4). Independent analyst reproduced all 5 operating-point simulations from scratch using only the SOP and archived input files; NIH predictions agreed within 0.3%. Peer review of mesh generation, boundary condition assignment, and post-processing scripts completed by senior engineer. Automated input-file validation script catches common parameter errors before job submission."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-mrl5",
      "rationale": "RANS k-omega SST turbulence model selected after systematic comparison of five turbulence closure models (standard k-eps, realizable k-eps, k-omega SST, RSM, and LES) against PIV data. k-omega SST achieved lowest velocity-field RMSE (3.8%) and best captured adverse pressure gradient separation in the volute. Power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen et al. coefficients updated per Zhang et al. 2011) validated against RBC lysis data in Couette viscometer. Model-form uncertainty quantified via alternative-model ensemble (5 turbulence models): 90th-percentile NIH spread = ±12%, included in total UQ budget."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-inputs-mrl5",
      "rationale": "All 12 model input parameters characterized with probability distributions derived from experimental measurements or literature meta-analysis. Inlet velocity profile: measured by LDV (±1.2%); blood viscosity: Carreau-Yasuda fit to 30-sample rheometry dataset (95% CI reported); hemolysis model coefficients: Bayesian posterior from 120 Couette lysis experiments. Input uncertainty propagated via 10 000-sample Latin hypercube Monte Carlo. Sobol indices identify hemolysis exponent C as dominant (S_T = 0.61); targeted additional experiments planned to reduce this uncertainty by 40% in next assessment cycle."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-samples-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Hemolysis experiments performed using leukoreduced packed red blood cells from 8 independent donor units (ABO-matched, hematocrit 40 ± 2%). Sample-to-sample variability characterized: inter-donor NIH CV = 7.2%, within acceptable range per ASTM F1841 guidance. Experimental uncertainty budget includes sample variability as explicit term. Statistical power analysis confirms n = 8 donors provides 80% power to detect 15% NIH difference at α = 0.05. Sample traceability maintained via chain-of-custody documentation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/input-equivalency-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Systematic comparison of simulation input parameters against experimental conditions performed using equivalency matrix (13 parameters × 5 operating conditions). Dimensional analysis confirms dynamic similarity: Reynolds number match within 1.5%, Womersley number within 2.1%. Fluid rheology equivalency: blood analog viscosity curve matches in-vivo data within measurement uncertainty across shear rate range 10–10 000 s⁻¹. Geometric equivalency: pump CAD model updated to reflect CMM-measured as-built dimensions. All equivalency assessments documented in report EQ-COU2-2025 with quantitative similarity metrics."
    }
